    value: 盂
english:
  title: Another Poem of Passing Thoughts
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There is a strange man who sells medicine,
    always hanging his sign in the marketplace.
    He points to Penglai Mountain for me,
    far and distant at heaven's corner.

    You should guard against desire,
    even the sacred dragon falls to the butcher's blade.
    He grants me the Blue Jade Formula,
    gifts me the Pearl of the Bright Moon.

    From this moment I abandon the ornate and splendid,
    and sing loudly of the simple way.
    At dawn I climb the peak of Mount Tai,
    and the Eastern Sea becomes no larger than a cup.

    Looking down, I trace the footprints of ancients,
    sweeeping my eyes across the maps of lands.
    Rise and fall follow the same track,
    victory and defeat are truly mere games of chance.
    Sun and moon roll like wagon wheels—
    this is not the pallor of the scholar's way.

    Returning, I guard the mystic gate,
    understanding how one source divides into myriad forms.
    The green and verdant pines of cold mountain streams,
    the distant reeds of the spring waterside—
    Though heaven's enclosure holds all things,
    the enlightened may yet escape its bounds.

    When one obtains the elixir through the proper measure,
    one rides the crane through clouds of blue forever.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Penglai Mountain (蓬萊山): A legendary island in Chinese mythology, representing the realm of immortals and spiritual enlightenment.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Blue Jade Formula and Pearl of the Bright Moon: Mystical teachings and gifts symbolizing esoteric wisdom and spiritual instruction.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mount Tai (泰山): One of the five sacred mountains in Chinese tradition, representing the axis of heaven and earth.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The mystic gate (玄牝): A Daoist concept referring to the gateway to the mysterious feminine principle of the Tao.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The measure (刀圭): A small measure of medicine used to obtain immortality in Daoist alchemy.'
